  "title": "4.4 INTERACTION WITH MAJOR STAKEHOLDERS",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "80ebf8378e18263a",
      "text": "Focus group discussions with the major stakeholders in the conflict produced interesting yet instructive results. Some of the people discussed with include representatives of the farmers, the hunters and the Bororo Fulanis. Highlights of the discussions are as follows:"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b2dd094e9b3a12c6",
      "text": "**Interaction with Farmers**"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e9042c830ba5282e",
      "text": "Mr Idowu Owoade, Chairman All Farmers Association of Nigeria [ALFAN], Saki West Local Government on Wednesday, 13th November, 2013 facilitated the discussion with farmers. The farmers stated that they were law abiding citizens but that the incessant attacks by the Bororo Fulanis had become a great challenge to them. Mr. Owoade recalled the various attacks on the farmers by the Bororo herdsmen and how they entered their farms and destroyed their crops with impunity.  "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "bf0f534a08f42719",
      "text": "He said whenever they were challenged, they responded in a defiant manner. He recounted a recent experience when a Bororo Fulani approached a farmer requesting that he (the farmer) should allow his cattle to feed on the farmers’ crop. Naturally, the farmer refused but by the following morning when the farmer went back to his farm, it had been plundered and the whole crop eaten up. The reaction of the farmer could be imagined!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b863ec76fe42f6f2",
      "text": "The farmers’ viewpoint was that governments’ handling of the conflict had not been helpful because they got the impression that government could not deal effectively with the Bororo Fulanis. They alleged that government had failed to intervene to deal with the problem in spite of overwhelming evidence of invasion of their farms and mindless destruction of their crops. Mr Owoade recalled a recent meeting   arranged by the State Government in Ibadan on the conflict. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7f2a0163c1e0cf1c",
      "text": "When the parties narrated their cases at the meeting, government could not make any pronouncement other than appealing to both sides to keep the peace. In such a situation, he contended, the farmers had no choice than to defend themselves and protect their properties.  "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "24accdf3ea50b961",
      "text": "When asked about the old relationship between farmers and Fulanis, the farmers said that they had no problems with old Fulanis [whom they called Fulani ilu] before the arrival of Bororos. They recalled that they had been living harmoniously with these Fulanis some of whom have integrated fully with the Yorubas. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "84dcf42562cd4241",
      "text": "According to the farmers, in the rare cases when Fulani ilus’ cattle strayed into farms, they would settle with farmers without acrimony. Cases of cattle eating up the crops of farmers were relatively few and when they occurred, Fulani elders would intervene, settle the rift and pay compensation.  They also alleged that there was no love lost between Fulani ilu and the farmers."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1a782d8ac75e982d",
      "text": "On the issue of perception, the farmers used derogatory language to describe the Bororos, referring to them as stateless and homeless people who roamed about destroying other people’s means of livelihood in a callous way."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ca9c8c245ec04d46",
      "text": "One farmer recounted his experience which although pathetic, was said to be a common occurrence especially among younger farmers in the area. He had farmed in three locations in succession and on each occasion, the cattle of the Bororos had eaten up his farms. In desperation, he had to abandon farming and resorted to doing commercial motorcycle work (Okada) and it has now become his permanent preoccupation. He obviously preferred the Okada job  because according to him  as at the time of the interview he had become a “proud owner of his own Okada motorcycle!”"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f6dfc94f58a0255c",
      "text": "When asked to suggest lasting solutions to the problem, the farmers said that it was up to government to create grazing zones for the itinerant Bororos so that they could stop straying into their farms and eating up their crops."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "744e9be0029ddd96",
      "text": "**Interaction with Fulanis**"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "8d462eb8b01dd02a",
      "text": "Alhaj Bashiru Sarkin Fulani led the Fulanis and according to them, it was not their desire to enter farms and destroy crops but since their animals had to survive when faced with scarcity of food and water. They further stated that people never realized the kind of agony they passed through in such situation adding that it was always stressful. They claimed that scarcity of food and water for their flocks had made herding a very tedious vocation. They asserted that just as human beings had the right to survive so are cattle."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1dd2e258dd0c8f60",
      "text": "When confronted with the alleged killing and maiming of farmers, the Fulanis claimed that they were usually provoked to fight either to defend themselves or when their cattle are seized on the allegation that they have destroyed the farms, an allegation which, according to them, could either not be established or at best, exaggerated.  "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0d90ba3f05788183",
      "text": "The Fulanis further remarked that although  they would like to pay compensation to farmers, most of the time  such claims were astronomically high and fraudulent, hence their refusal to pay. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d756f6069952263e",
      "text": "On the role of security agents, the Fulanis denied bribing them adding that it was these agents that saved them from the tyranny of the farmers and the local people."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ab1bc9d7bbbf4345",
      "text": "On the role of government, the Fulanis deprecated the attitude of governments especially at the Local and State levels which were said to be partial or even hostile to them. They wanted greater recognition for the Sarkin Fulanis saying that they should be on government pay role if they would be in a position to checkmate the notorious Bororo Fulanis."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "97921082da2c3dc7",
      "text": "On permanent solution(s) to the problem, the Fulanis remarked that government should create grazing reserves for them and restore their cattle routes which the farmers have infiltrated and converted to farms.   "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "42f7c87100a58e21",
      "text": "**Interaction with Hunters**"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "07630bbadb4c871f",
      "text": "The hunters were led by Primate Samson Ojoawo. He stated that as law abiding citizens, they do not intervene in conflicts unless they were invited to do so, usually by the paramount ruler of the town. Theirs was to protect their kith and kin from the incessant maiming and killing by the Bororo Fulani herdsmen. According to the hunters, it was never a pleasant assignment yet they had to do it to protect their people and sometimes retaliate the assault of the herdsmen. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4661231f0e612f3e",
      "text": "When asked about the possibility of the innocent ones being made to suffer for other people’s offence, they said that Bororos were the same and the fact that one was not involved in one incident did not mean that he had not committed that kind of heinous offence before or that he would not do so in future! "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "31e86eacbe1d942a",
      "text": "In proffering solution to the problem, they suggested that the Bororos should leave Saki and, indeed, Oke Ogun completely, wondering why the flock of some rich men  from faraway places should be used in a mindless way to destroy other people’s properties and kill them in the process."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "281760591c9d5e0c",
      "text": "Next section **[[4.5 RECENT INTERVENTIONS IN THE CONFLICT]]**"
